#This study predicts 2026 peak cherry blossom bloom dates at five international 
#sites using a temperature-driven statistical modeling framework. Historical
#bloom records were combined with daily meteorological observations from NOAA’s
#Global Historical Climatology Network (GHCN). The response variable was peak
#bloom day-of-year (DOY). Further prediction was done by comparing past winters 
#with comparable temperatures to the current years temperatures.

#Exploratory analysis showed a consistent long-term decline in bloom DOY across
#sites since 1880, suggesting earlier flowering over time. However, simple 
#linear time trends risk extrapolation error and do not incorporate biological
#mechanisms. Therefore, temperature-based predictors were incorporated.

#Winter temperature was selected as the primary feature due to its biological 
#relevance to dormancy release and chilling accumulation. For each site, average
#daily maximum temperature (TMAX) was computed for December–February winters,
#aligning December with the subsequent bloom year. Temperatures were converted 
#from tenths of degrees Celsius to degrees Celsius.

#A multiple linear regression model was fitted with bloom DOY as the response 
#and location, year, and average winter TMAX as predictors. This allowed 
#separation of long-term trends from interannual climatic variability. 
#Predictions were generated using both projected 2026 winter temperatures 
#(based on site-specific temperature trends) and observed winter temperatures to date.

#To reduce dependence on parametric assumptions, an analogue-based forecasting 
#approach was also implemented. For each site, the five historical winters with
#average temperatures most similar to winter 2026 (observed to date) were
#identified. The corresponding bloom DOYs were averaged to produce a 
#nonparametric prediction. This analogue method provides robustness against
#model misspecification and offers interpretable uncertainty based on historical 
#variability.

#Across all sites, warmer winters were associated with earlier bloom dates. 
#The analogue and regression-based forecasts were broadly consistent, suggesting
#that winter temperature captures a meaningful component of bloom timing variability.

#This framework balances mechanistic interpretability with statistical rigor.
#By incorporating both parametric regression and historical analogues, 
#it provides transparent, climate-informed forecasts while remaining computationally
#simple and reproducible."



